Bring a medium #pot{} of salted water to a boil. Wash and dry produce.

Peel and mince @garlic{1%clove}. Trim and cut @scallions{2}(trimmed and cut crosswise into 1-inch pieces) crosswise into 1-inch pieces; thinly slice one-quarter of the scallion greens. Trim and peel @carrots{3%oz}(peeled); grate on the largest holes of a #box grater{}. Roughly chop @peanuts{1/2%oz}(roughly chopped).

In a small #bowl{}, whisk together @sweet soy glaze{4%tablespoon}, @pork ramen stock concentrate{1}, half the @Szechuan paste{2%tablespoon}, half the @white wine vinegar{5%teaspoon}, half the @peanut butter{1.15%oz}, @sugar{1.5%teaspoon}, @water{1/4%cup}, and @chili flakes{1%teaspoon} to taste until smooth.
> For 4 servings, use all the Szechuan paste, all the vinegar, all the peanut butter, 3 tsp sugar, and 1⁄3 cup water.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{1%teaspoon} in a large #pan{} over medium-high heat. Add @ground pork{10%oz}. Using a #spatula{}, press into an even layer. Cook, undisturbed, until browned on bottom, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Break up meat into pieces and continue cooking until pork is cooked through, ~{2-4%minutes} more.

Add garlic and scallion pieces to pan with pork; cook until fragrant, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Stir in sauce; cook until reduced and thickened slightly, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Once water is boiling, add @ramen noodles{4.5%oz} to pot. Cook, stirring occasionally, until tender, ~{1-2%minutes}. Drain and thoroughly rinse under cold water, at least ~{30%seconds}.
> This stops cooking and helps prevent sticky noodles.

Add drained noodles, carrot, and @butter{1%tablespoon} to pan with pork mixture. Toss until noodles are warmed through and everything is thoroughly combined, ~{1-2%minutes}.
> TIP: If needed, stir in water a splash at a time until noodles are thoroughly coated in sauce.

Taste and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Divide stir-fry between bowls. Top with sliced scallion greens, peanuts, and remaining chili flakes to taste. Serve.

> Ground Pork is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 160º.

> For 4 servings, use 2 TBSP butter (instead of 1 TBSP).